Dear Steve,=0A=
=0A=
When an elementary (base) topos S is specified, I use "S-bounded topos" to =
mean the pair (E, e), with E an elementary topos and e: E--> S a (bounded) =
geometric morphism. When S =3D Set (a model of ZFC) and E an arbitrary elem=
entary topos, then there is a most one geometric morphism e:E---> Set, so i=
n that case the latter need not be specified. I therefore use "E is a Groth=
endieck topos" to mean  "E is an elementary topos bounded over Sets".  The =
latter has been shown to be equivalent to what Grothendieck meant by it.=0A=
=0A=
Best regards,=0A=
Marta=0A=
